# CMS-Compatible Architecture (Headless CMS Ready)

Build so Strapi, Directus, or similar can plug in later **without major refactors**. Target a **structured, form-based CMS**, not a visual page builder.

**What breaks at scale:** inconsistent schemas, uncontrolled components, duplicated or tangled content relationships, and one-off dev decisions. **Guardrails** (versions, contracts, layers, references, migration boundary) live in **Content System Principles**—apply both files together.

## Core principle

- **CMS**: structured data + ordered sections
- **Frontend**: layout, rendering, logic

## 1. Separation of concerns

- **Content**: external (local JSON or API-ready); never embedded in UI logic
- **Structure**: expressed in data (section types, order), not hardcoded in templates
- **UI**: presentational only; no fetching or CMS field names in leaf components

Do not mix these layers.

## 2. No hardcoded content

- No static marketing copy, labels, or image URLs inside feature/page components
- Pass all copy and media **via props** (after adapters)
- Exceptions: true UI chrome only (e.g. “Close”, “Menu”) if unavoidable—keep minimal

## 3. Ordered section-based pages

- Support `sections[]` with `type`, `version`, `order`, and `data` (optional `variant` from a fixed set)
- **Resolver**: map `type → component` in one place; do not hardcode section order in templates

```js
[
  { type: "hero", version: 1, order: 1, data: { title, description, image, cta } },
  { type: "features", version: 1, order: 2, data: { items: [...] } }
]
```

## 4. Limited section types

- **Max ~10–12** reusable section types; reuse across pages
- Avoid one-off or page-specific section components—extend a shared type with data instead
- **Highest ROI:** maintain an explicit catalog of allowed section types and their **schemas** (required/optional fields, `version`)—that is where most cross-project consistency comes from

## 5. CMS-friendly data shape

- Flat, predictable fields; avoid deep nesting and UI-specific blobs
- Consistent names: `title`, `description`, `image`, `cta` (and project-wide conventions)

## 6. Adapter layer

- UI components do not consume raw API/CMS payloads
- Normalize in **adapters or composables** so response shape changes stay at the boundary

## 7. Fixed vs flexible pages

- **Fixed schema** for predictable routes (e.g. room detail: known fields)
- **Section arrays** only where editorial flexibility is required (e.g. homepage)
- Do not default every page to fully dynamic sections

## 8. Blog (structured, not block-based)

- Fixed schema: `title`, `slug`, `content`, `cover_image`, `seo`, etc.
- **Not** a section-builder page; treat as its own content type

## 9. Slug-based routing

- Prefer dynamic routes (e.g. `[slug].vue` / file-based equivalent)
- No hardcoded canonical URLs inside presentational components

## 10. SEO as data

- `seo` as a separate object: `meta_title`, `meta_description`, `og_image`, etc.
- Set meta in layout/page/composable—not inside dumb UI components

## 11. UI library abstraction

- Page/feature components use **wrappers** (`BaseButton`, `BaseCard`, …)
- Do not import PrimeVue (or similar) directly in domain/section components

## 12. CMS-agnostic code

- No Strapi- or Directus-specific field names or response shapes outside adapters
- Types and mocks should mirror **normalized** app models, not vendor JSON

## Preflight (before implementing)

1. Can this be stored in a **relational** headless CMS?
2. Can a **non-visual** editor manage it?
3. Am I **pushing layout choices into data**? If any answer is no, adjust first.

**Before adding a new pattern or rule:** Will it reduce future inconsistency? Will it help a junior dev make fewer mistakes? Will it apply across **all** hotel projects? If not, skip (YAGNI).

## Constraints

- Minimal, repeatable patterns; avoid overengineering
- Clarity and consistency over maximum flexibility
